He has recently been attempting (with little success) to distract from his union problems by whipping up a fuss over Lynton Crosby, David Cameron’s adviser. But aside from the synthetic nature of the outrage, the state of Mr Crosby’s client list is hardly as serious a matter as the very future of the Labour Party. Mr Miliband – who owes his position to the union block vote – cannot be a credible leader unless he repudiates Mr McCluskey and his ilk, and proves that the Blair years were not just a brief interregnum in Labour’s long march to the Left. The price of that credibility will be to risk bankrupting his party. It is not a pretty choice.
